The '''2011 Chişinău explosion''' was a car explosion in the center of [[Chişinău]], the capital of [[Moldova]]. The explosion killed the Moldovan tennis federation chief, Igor Turcan.<ref name="bbc">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-13680308 Car blast kills Moldovan tennis chief Igor Turca] ''[[BBC News]]'' 7 June 2011</ref><ref>[http://rt.com/news/car-bomb-blasts-capital/ Car blast in Moldovan capital] ''[[Russia Today]]'' 7 June</ref> He was heading the campaign for an independent candidate in last weekend's mayoral election.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/europe/moldovan-tennis-chief-dies-in-car-explosion-2294302.html Moldovan tennis chief dies in car explosion] ''[[The Independent]]'' 8 June 2011</ref>

Turcan was passing by a model [[Lada]] automobile, which had [[Russia]]n number plates, when it blew up.<ref name="bbc" />  Turcan was sent to hospital and later died of serious injuries.<ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/06/07/moldova-blast-victim-idUSLDE7561AY20110607 Man dies from injuries after Moldovan car blast] ''[[Reuters]]'' 7 June 2011</ref> The police said no one else was killed or injured in the explosion.<ref>[http://www.speroforum.com/a/55073/Car-Blast-In-Moldovan-Capital-Kills-Tennis-Official Car Blast In Moldovan Capital Kills Tennis Official] ''[[Spero News]]'' 7 June 2011</ref> An earlier eyewitness report had said three people were killed.<ref>[http://www.novinite.com/view_news.php?id=129048 Car Blast Rocks Moldova's Capital] ''[[Novinite.com]]'' 7 June 2011</ref>

Turcan's deputy described the explosion as an "[[assassination]]" but the [[Prime Minister of Moldova]], [[Vlad Filat]], said it was too early to draw conclusions about what happened.<ref name="bbc" />

