__NOTOC__

[[File:Otton Mathilde croix.jpg|thumb|upright|Duke Otto (''Otto dux'') and his sister, abbess [[Mathilde, Abbess of Essen|Mathilde]] (''Mahthild abba''),<br>a detail on the [[Cross of Otto and Mathilde]]]]
'''Otto I''' (born 954, died 31 October or 1 November 982) was the [[Duke of Swabia]] from 973 and [[Duke of Bavaria]] from 976. He was a member of the [[Ottonian dynasty]], the only son of Duke [[Liudolf, Duke of Swabia|Liudolf of Swabia]] and his wife Ida, and thus a grandson of the Emperor [[Otto I]] and his Anglo-Saxon wife [[Eadgyth]]. His sister [[Mathilde, Abbess of Essen|Mathilde]] was the abbess of [[Essen Abbey]].{{sfn|Zotz|1998|pp=694–95}}

Otto was only three years old when his father died in 957. He was raised at the court of his grandfather, Otto I, who seems to have adopted him and raised him alongside his own son, the future Emperor [[Otto II]], born late in 955. The latter regarded him as both "nephew and brother" (''nepos ac frater'').{{sfn|Zotz|1998|pp=694–95}} When the childless Duke [[Burchard III of Swabia]] died in 973, Otto II transferred the Swabian duchy to his nineteen-year-old nephew and brother, whose father had been Burchard's predecessor.{{sfn|Zotz|1998|pp=694–95}} The elder Otto became a close confidante of his younger sovereign.

In 976 the imprisoned Duke [[Henry the Wrangler]] of Bavaria was formally dismissed from office for rebellion. In his place the emperor appointed Otto of Swabia, who became the first ruler of two duchies in medieval Germany.{{sfn|Zotz|1998|pp=694–95}} The [[Duchy of Carinthia]] and the [[March of the Nordgau]] were also taken from Henry, but were not bestowed on Otto, thus their history is separate from that of Bavaria from this point on.{{sfn|Duckett|1967|p=99}}{{sfn|Stälin|1886|p=725}} In 977, while the emperor was campaigning elsewhere, Otto helped crush the [[War of the Three Henries (977–978)|revolt of the Three Henries]]—the deposed duke of Bavaria, Bishop [[Henry I (bishop of Augsburg)|Henry I of Augsburg]] and Duke [[Henry III, Duke of Bavaria|Henry I of Carinthia]]—by successfully besieging the leaders in [[Passau]].{{sfn|Zotz|1998|pp=694–95}} The army of Bavarians that was ambushed by [[Boleslaus I of Bohemia]] near [[Plzeň]] while on its way to join the emperor at this time may have been sent by Duke Otto.{{sfn|Duckett|1967|p=99}}{{sfn|Stälin|1886|p=725}}

In 980 Otto accompanied the emperor on his south Italian campaign, fighting both the [[Byzantine Empire|Byzantines]] and the [[Emirate of Sicily|Sicilian Arabs]]. He survived the [[Battle of Stilo|defeat near Crotone]] on 13/14 July 982 and a subsequent ambush by an Arab force. Assigned to take the news of the campaign back to Germany, he died ''en route'', of wounds received in battle, either 31 October or 1 November, at [[Lucca]].{{sfn|Zotz|1998|pp=694–95}} His father had also died south of the Alps. His family brought his body back and had it buried in the [[:de:St. Peter und Alexander (Aschaffenburg)|collegiate church of Saints Peter and Alexander]] at [[Aschaffenburg]], which Otto had generously endowed.{{sfn|Zotz|1998|pp=694–95}} His death is noted in the contemporary Abingdon version of the ''[[Anglo-Saxon Chronicle]]'': "And then, as he went home, his [the emperor's] brother's son, who was called Otto, passed away; and he was the son of the [[aetheling]] Liudolf, and this Liudolf was son of Otto the Elder and King Edward's daughter".{{sfn|Swanton|1998|p=124|ps=. The "King Edward" is [[Edward the Elder]].}}{{sfn|Whitbread|1959|pp=577–78|ps=: and þa he hamweard for . þa forðferde his broþor sunu . se wæs haten Odda . and he wæs Leodulfes sunu æþelinges . and se Leodulf wæs þæs ealdan Oddan sunu . and Eadweardes cininges dohtor sunu.}}

Otto's sister Mathilde endowed a precious ''[[crux gemmata]]'' (jewelled cross), the [[Cross of Otto and Mathilde]], which is kept in the [[Essen Cathedral Treasury]]; the siblings are pictured on it. Otto never married and left no children.{{sfn|Stälin|1886|p=726}}

