'''Paddy''' (Pigeon number NPS.43.9451)<ref>[http://www.pdsa.org.uk/page309_3.html PDSA website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080922204813/http://www.pdsa.org.uk/page309_3.html |date=2008-09-22 }}, Dickin Medal awardees, retrieved 2006-02-26</ref> was an [[Ireland|Irish]] [[carrier pigeon]] awarded the [[Dickin Medal]] after being the fastest pigeon to arrive back in [[England]] with news of the success of the [[invasion of Normandy|D-Day invasion]], out of hundreds dispatched. He flew 230 miles across the [[English Channel]] in four hours and fifty minutes,<ref>[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article3033257.ece Times Online], "Top 50 greatest sporting animals", retrieved 2008-04-26</ref> the fastest recorded crossing, and was awarded the medal on 1 September 1944, just under three months after the crossing.<ref>[http://observer.guardian.co.uk/magazine/story/0,,2012830,00.html Observer magazine] Dickin medal awardees, retrieved 2006-02-26</ref> Paddy was trained by Andrew Hughes of [[Carnlough]] and is the only animal in Ireland to be awarded this medal.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/northernireland/yourplaceandmine/topics/war/dday_news.shtml BBC Your Place and Mine], "Paddy Power", retrieved 2008-04-26</ref>
The medal citation reads,
{{quote|"For the best recorded time with a message from the Normandy Operations, while serving with the RAF in June, 1944."}} 
His medal was sold at auction for almost £7,000 in September 1999.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/northern_ireland/458238.stm BBC News website], "Northern Ireland
Fancier flies away with pigeon medal", retrieved 2006-02-26</ref>

